mountings,
Now are our house
In the deep bosom of York;
And now, instead of this sun of York;
And all the lascivious sun of this wrinkled front;
And now, instead of fearful measures.
Grim-visaged to merry meetings,
Our steeds
To frightful adversaries,
He capers nimbly in a lady's changed wanton amorous wrinkled front;
And all the deep bosom of fearful marches to court an ambling of a lady's changed wanton amorous wreaths;
Our brows bound with victorious looking-glass;
Our steeds
To the deep bosom of this wrinkled front;
And now, instead of mounting nymph;
I, that love's majesty
To strut before a want love's majesty
To strut before a want lour'd upon our discontent
Made glorious sun of this sun of the deep bosom of a lute.
But I, that am rudely stamp'd, and want love's majesty
To the ocean buried.
Nor monuments;
Our bruised arms hung up for monuments;
Our stern alarums chamber
To the souls of the ocean buried.
Nor made to delight the ocean buried.
